    <section>
      <h2>Step 5: Operate and Stay Compliant</h2>
      <p>Receiving your license is the beginning of compliance, not the end. Maine's cannabis regulatory framework imposes ongoing requirements that must be met every day of operation.</p>

      <h3>METRC Seed-to-Sale Tracking</h3>
      <p>All Maine cannabis licensees must use METRC for inventory tracking from seed to sale. Every plant, every harvest batch, every product transfer, and every retail sale must be logged in METRC. The system is auditable — OCP can pull your METRC data at any time to verify that your physical inventory matches your reported inventory.</p>
      <p>METRC non-compliance is one of the most common sources of enforcement action. Discrepancies between physical inventory and METRC records — even minor ones — trigger investigation. Operators build compliance into every operational touchpoint: receiving protocols that verify METRC tags on incoming products, sales procedures that sync with METRC in real time, and weekly inventory reconciliations that catch discrepancies before they become problems.</p>

      <h3>Cash-Only Operations</h3>
      <p>Because cannabis remains federally illegal, most banks will not transact with cannabis businesses. Maine dispensaries operate almost entirely in cash. This creates real operational challenges: secure cash handling, cash drops to banks (where available), cash payroll for employees who can't receive direct deposit, and cash management protocols that prevent internal theft.</p>
      <p>Some credit unions and state-chartered banks have developed cannabis banking programs, though service is not universal and fee structures are higher than for comparable non-cannabis businesses. Many Maine dispensaries maintain a banking relationship for deposit-only purposes and manage the majority of their cash flow in cash.</p>

      <h3>OCP Audit and Reporting Requirements</h3>
      <p>OCP conducts periodic compliance audits of licensed dispensaries. Audits examine inventory records, METRC data, transaction logs, and physical facility compliance. Operators must maintain records for a minimum of five years — cultivation records, purchase agreements, sales records, and compliance documentation. OCP typically provides 48 hours notice of routine audits, though the agency can conduct unannounced inspections for cause.</p>
    </section>

