        <p>David opened his dispensary in Bangor in early 2025 after 14 months of work.</p>
      <p>He started by spending three weeks confirming which municipalities allowed dispensaries. He contacted every city clerk in Penobscot County before identifying Bangor as his target.</p>
      <p>He found a 2,200 square foot retail location on Main Street. He confirmed with the city planner that it met all buffer requirements. He spent $4,500 in architectural fees on a facility plan before submitting his municipal application.</p>
        <p>The municipal phase took 11 weeks. The planning board hearing was straightforward.</p>
      <p>David had proactively contacted adjacent property owners and addressed their concerns before the meeting. He brought a letter from the downtown business association in support of his application. The city council approved his license on a 6-1 vote.</p>
        <p>His OCP application took 10 weeks to process. He hired a consultant with Maine cannabis experience. She reviewed his application before submission and flagged two potential deficiency areas: camera placement specs and METRC vendor documentation. David addressed these before submitting.</p>
      <p>The pre-operation inspection took four hours and passed with zero deficiencies.</p>
        <p>"The inspection was nerve-wracking, but if your application is accurate and your facility actually matches what you submitted, it's manageable," David says. "We opened on a Thursday. Our first week we did $31,000 in sales. First-year revenue was $1.4 million."</p>
        <p class="attribution">— Case study based on operator interview, Bangor, Maine (2025)</p>
