      <h3>Total Investment Range</h3>
      <p>Combining build-out and first-year operating costs, total startup investment typically ranges from $375,000 to $750,000 for a Portland dispensary. For a rural Maine location, it ranges from $250,000 to $500,000.</p>
      <p>These estimates assume you are leasing rather than purchasing real estate. Purchasing a commercial property for a dispensary adds significant capital requirements but eliminates monthly lease costs.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What You Cannot Do in Maine (Legal Restrictions)</h2>
      <p>Maine's cannabis regulations impose specific prohibitions that apply to all licensees. Compliance isn't optional — violations can result in license suspension, revocation, monetary penalties, and in serious cases, criminal referral.</p>

      <h3>Operating Without Proper Licensing</h3>
      <p>You cannot operate a dispensary without both a valid municipal authorization and a state OCP license. Operating without a license is a criminal offense in Maine, not merely a civil violation. The state's adult-use cannabis statutes impose specific penalties for unlicensed cannabis commerce.</p>

      <h3>Sales to Minors and Over-Purchase Limits</h3>
      <p>Dispensaries cannot sell to anyone under 21 years of age — this is non-negotiable and verified by ID check at every transaction. Maine law also imposes a per-transaction purchase limit of 2.5 ounces of cannabis flower for adult-use customers. You cannot complete a transaction that exceeds this limit, and you cannot structure transactions to circumvent the limit.</p>

      <h3>Untaxed or Untracked Products</h3>
      <p>All cannabis products sold in Maine must be sourced from licensed Maine cultivators or processors and must have valid METRC tags throughout the supply chain. You cannot purchase products from unlicensed sources, and you cannot sell any product that lacks a valid METRC chain-of-custody record. This applies to samples, employee purchases, and any other disposition of product — every gram must be tracked.</p>

      <h3>Advertising Restrictions</h3>
      <p>Cannabis advertising in Maine cannot target minors, cannot make false or misleading claims, and cannot depict consumption. Outdoor advertising within 500 feet of a school is prohibited. Many new operators don't realize how restrictive the advertising rules are — review OCP's advertising guidelines carefully before designing any marketing materials.</p>

      <Callout title="Compliance Is Your License" type="passion">
        Every Maine cannabis license is a privilege, not a right. OCP takes compliance seriously and has revoked licenses for violations that some operators considered minor. Build compliance into your operations from day one — not as an afterthought. A single substantiated compliance violation can jeopardize everything you've built.
      </Callout>
    </section>

